WEBVTT

00:06.172 --> 00:07.340
ANGELA: Do you like spaghetti?

00:07.424 --> 00:09.467
-NATHAN FIELDER: I do.
-ANGELA: Great.

00:12.345 --> 00:13.596
When you were young,
did you ever hate

00:13.680 --> 00:14.806
one of your parents?

00:15.849 --> 00:18.309
-(CLATTERING)
-NATHAN: I don't think so.

00:18.393 --> 00:21.646
-No? I did. I hated my dad.
-NATHAN: Oh, really?

00:21.730 --> 00:23.231
I was very angry at him

00:23.314 --> 00:27.944
because he wasn't there.
I put my parents through hell.

00:28.611 --> 00:30.071
I drank like a fish.

00:30.155 --> 00:35.201
-What did you drink?
-Vodka, tequila. I did drugs.

00:35.994 --> 00:37.370
Marijuana...

00:38.621 --> 00:41.458
-acid.
-You did acid?

00:41.541 --> 00:43.960
-Yep.
-NATHAN: What?

00:44.043 --> 00:45.879
-Cocaine.
-You did cocaine?

00:45.962 --> 00:47.172
(SMACKS LIPS) Yep.

00:48.882 --> 00:50.133
(CLICKS TONGUE) And that sent me

00:50.216 --> 00:52.844
into a lot
of destructive behaviors.

00:52.927 --> 00:54.012
NATHAN: Mm-hmm.

00:59.267 --> 01:01.144
What are you doing
with the noodles there?

01:01.227 --> 01:03.313
-I'm seeing how done they are.
-NATHAN: Oh, okay.

01:03.396 --> 01:04.522
ANGELA: Yeah.

01:04.606 --> 01:08.568
♪ ("THE REHEARSAL"
THEME MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

01:08.651 --> 01:11.279
NATHAN: It's beautiful
in rural Oregon.

01:11.362 --> 01:12.947
And the town of Eagle Creek,

01:13.031 --> 01:16.993
my home base for this project,
definitely has a lot to offer.

01:18.203 --> 01:20.330
But if what you need
is a consistent supply

01:20.413 --> 01:21.956
of professional actors

01:22.040 --> 01:24.083
for all the rehearsals
you have in the works...

01:24.167 --> 01:25.543
-ANGELA: Bye.
-Bye. See you later.

01:25.627 --> 01:29.005
NATHAN: ...you need to take
regular trips to a big city.

01:29.088 --> 01:32.008
You need to go
where the actors are.

01:32.091 --> 01:34.177
♪ (MILD TEMPO MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

01:34.260 --> 01:35.428
NATHAN: During this process,

01:35.512 --> 01:38.765
I've discovered that
an actor's sense of authenticity

01:38.848 --> 01:41.810
can vary vastly
from one to another.

01:41.893 --> 01:43.394
And I wanted a way to create

01:43.478 --> 01:45.688
a standard for the level
of realism

01:45.772 --> 01:47.732
I needed for this project.

01:49.317 --> 01:51.820
I had recently launched
The Fielder Method Studio

01:51.903 --> 01:56.491
in LA's NoHo Arts District
as a recruitment camp of sorts,

01:56.574 --> 01:58.993
to find and train
up-and-coming actors

01:59.077 --> 02:02.330
in the specific techniques
needed for this show.

02:02.413 --> 02:05.917
Unlike a normal role
where the worst thing

02:06.000 --> 02:09.671
that can happen is, you know,
someone changes the channel

02:09.754 --> 02:11.506
if they don't like
your performance,

02:11.589 --> 02:14.133
you know what I mean.
Like, with this show,

02:14.217 --> 02:15.677
if your performance
isn't accurate,

02:15.760 --> 02:17.554
you could ruin someone's life.

02:17.637 --> 02:18.721
♪ (SOFT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

02:18.805 --> 02:20.515
NATHAN: Preparing an actor
for a rehearsal

02:20.598 --> 02:22.267
is sort of like a spy mission.

02:22.350 --> 02:24.853
And I wanted them to learn
how to do it themselves,

02:24.936 --> 02:28.106
as well as improve on mistakes
we had made in the past.

02:28.189 --> 02:31.192
So, is your method based upon,
like, literally a slice of life

02:31.276 --> 02:33.361
with this person
and then creating reenactments

02:33.444 --> 02:35.864
-based off this one experience?
-My point is

02:35.947 --> 02:38.241
-that this didn't go far enough.
-Okay.

02:38.324 --> 02:40.451
Sounds like we're gonna
secretly follow somebody around

02:40.535 --> 02:42.161
-for a while.
-(CHUCKLES) Stalking?

02:42.245 --> 02:43.538
-Stalking?
-Yeah. Yes.

02:43.621 --> 02:44.706
-(ALL CHUCKLE)
-You guys--

02:44.789 --> 02:46.666
Okay, you guys are getting
ahead of this. Good.

02:46.749 --> 02:50.753
NATHAN: But I often find myself
intimidated by actors.

02:50.837 --> 02:53.590
Stella Adler says you can be
representational,

02:53.673 --> 02:55.592
which is action based.

02:55.675 --> 02:58.136
Or you could be
representational,

02:58.219 --> 02:59.596
which is behavior based.

03:00.138 --> 03:01.306
S-- S--

03:01.389 --> 03:02.891
-Stella Adler.
-Stella Adler.

03:02.974 --> 03:05.685
-And then, yeah.
-What is her thing?

03:05.768 --> 03:07.145
NATHAN: They have a way
of channeling

03:07.228 --> 03:10.940
other people's emotions
that I don't fully understand.

03:11.024 --> 03:13.568
The most playful chakra
is your third eye, right?

03:13.651 --> 03:15.403
It's your creative mind
as an actor.

03:15.486 --> 03:16.779
That's where you wanna live.

03:16.863 --> 03:19.240
Just in hearing you talk
about this, um,

03:19.324 --> 03:21.743
it's like the Suzuki Method
which is physical

03:21.826 --> 03:22.869
-and it's about--
-Suzuki?

03:22.952 --> 03:24.829
Yeah, and it's about filling
the form.

03:24.913 --> 03:27.916
Okay. And what's the best way
to fill in the form?

03:27.999 --> 03:29.417
Just do the action.

03:29.500 --> 03:31.085
-Do the action.
-ACTOR: Yeah.

03:31.169 --> 03:33.212
Like in the deep reality
of the action.

03:33.296 --> 03:34.923
-Sure.
-THOMAS: Yeah.

03:35.006 --> 03:36.299
NATHAN: And by the time
I gave them

03:36.382 --> 03:40.053
their first assignment,
I was feeling a little insecure.

03:42.555 --> 03:44.641
Okay. So now, we're gonna put

03:44.724 --> 03:47.185
some of what you guys learned
today, into action.

03:47.268 --> 03:49.646
You're gonna go out
into the real world

03:49.729 --> 03:53.942
and pick a real person
to become your primary.

03:54.025 --> 03:57.070
And you're gonna secretly
observe and interact with them,

03:57.153 --> 03:59.864
and find out as much
as you can about them.

03:59.948 --> 04:02.200
And then, you're gonna come
back tomorrow

04:02.283 --> 04:04.577
dressed like them. Okay?

04:06.079 --> 04:07.455
Any other questions or...

04:09.415 --> 04:12.752
-Okay, cool. See you later.
-ACTOR 2: Bye.

04:12.835 --> 04:14.671
NATHAN: After spending time
with people,

04:14.754 --> 04:18.508
I'm often left wondering
what they actually think of me.

04:18.591 --> 04:23.346
So, once the class was gone,
I tried a little experiment.

04:23.429 --> 04:27.433
I decided to recreate the class
using different actors

04:27.517 --> 04:29.185
to portray each person,

04:29.269 --> 04:33.064
so I could relive the day
from a student's perspective.

04:34.232 --> 04:35.900
My hope was to gain insight

04:35.984 --> 04:38.277
into how each lesson
made them feel,

04:38.361 --> 04:40.613
so I could improve it
for tomorrow.

04:40.697 --> 04:42.657
With this show...

04:42.740 --> 04:44.784
if your performance
isn't accurate...

04:45.576 --> 04:47.578
you could ruin a person's life.

04:47.662 --> 04:50.456
NATHAN: I picked
a random student to inhabit.

04:50.540 --> 04:51.916
An actor named Thomas,

04:52.000 --> 04:54.210
who was sitting on the side
of the room.

04:54.293 --> 04:56.337
Putting myself in his headspace,

04:56.421 --> 04:58.673
I noticed this teacher
wasn't very good

04:58.756 --> 05:00.466
at connecting with us.

05:00.550 --> 05:03.052
Your character research
needs to be sourced

05:03.136 --> 05:04.303
through real-world interactions

05:04.387 --> 05:05.930
with the person
you're portraying.

05:06.014 --> 05:07.974
NATHAN: It didn't seem
like he had ever taught

05:08.057 --> 05:09.559
an acting class before.

05:09.642 --> 05:13.438
Is it weird... to put my name,
like, in a method?

05:13.521 --> 05:14.480
-Or...
-ALL: No.

05:14.564 --> 05:16.190
ACTOR: Everyone does that, yeah.

05:16.274 --> 05:17.900
NATHAN: I wondered
if my fellow students

05:17.984 --> 05:19.527
felt the same way.

05:19.610 --> 05:21.779
But I couldn't really see
their faces well

05:21.863 --> 05:24.657
because of how the chairs
were arranged.

05:24.741 --> 05:27.118
We were all facing forwards.

05:27.201 --> 05:28.578
And this formal environment

05:28.661 --> 05:31.247
made the whole class
a little less fun.

05:31.330 --> 05:33.416
So, your assignment
for the rest of the day is,

05:33.499 --> 05:35.376
you're gonna go out
into the real world

05:35.460 --> 05:37.378
and secretly observe
your primary.

05:37.462 --> 05:41.049
NATHAN: But it felt like
the method itself made sense.

05:41.132 --> 05:43.051
Nathan explained it all clearly

05:43.134 --> 05:45.595
and it was actually sort
of intriguing.

05:45.678 --> 05:47.930
Maybe there was something to it.

05:48.014 --> 05:51.434
I guess I'd have to keep taking
the class to find out.

05:57.356 --> 05:58.399
(DOOR CLICKS OPEN)

05:59.817 --> 06:01.486
-THOMAS: Hey.
-NATHAN: Hey.

06:01.569 --> 06:04.822
-We're circling. That's cool.
(CHUCKLES)
-Yeah, circle today.

06:04.906 --> 06:06.866
Hang out. Have a seat.
How's it going?

06:06.949 --> 06:09.285
It's good to see you. Hello.

06:09.368 --> 06:13.122
♪ (MILD TEMPO MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

06:13.206 --> 06:14.916
Um, I asked her how her day
was going,

06:14.999 --> 06:17.335
how long was her shift.
She's working till midnight.

06:17.418 --> 06:18.628
She's really tired.

06:18.711 --> 06:22.173
I found her Instagram
through geotags.

06:22.256 --> 06:23.424
-Wow.
-Then I found her Twitter

06:23.508 --> 06:25.051
-and I found her TikTok.
-NATHAN: Good. Good.

06:25.134 --> 06:26.427
-She's having...
-(ALL LAUGH)

06:26.511 --> 06:27.970
...she's having
a breast reduction soon.

06:28.054 --> 06:29.263
Her name is Amanda.

06:29.347 --> 06:32.100
NATHAN: I felt way more in sync
with the actors today.

06:32.183 --> 06:34.602
The vibe in the room felt
so much better.

06:34.685 --> 06:37.814
Yeah. So, my primary's name
is Henry. He is a barber.

06:37.897 --> 06:39.440
-You had to get
your hair cut then?
-Yeah.

06:39.524 --> 06:41.317
-You got a haircut?
-I got my hair cut and I--

06:41.400 --> 06:43.277
-Yeah, it was nice. Yeah.
-(ALL CHEER)

06:43.361 --> 06:45.488
-ACTOR: So, it was good
and like...
-Okay, cool. Good.

06:45.571 --> 06:47.490
NATHAN: But I noticed
some students were struggling

06:47.573 --> 06:48.699
with the assignment.

06:48.783 --> 06:52.078
-NATHAN: Thomas, what about you?
-(SMACKS LIPS) Uh...

06:52.161 --> 06:55.289
-Well, I went to an Acai Place.
-Acai?

06:55.373 --> 06:56.541
It's kinda like a smoothie bowl.

06:56.624 --> 06:57.792
NATHAN: Okay.

06:57.875 --> 06:59.460
NATHAN: And I thought
this would be a good opportunity

06:59.544 --> 07:01.796
to show them I knew
what I was doing.

07:01.879 --> 07:04.549
I noticed you didn't get
as-- as much, um...

07:04.632 --> 07:06.425
personal information
about your primary

07:06.509 --> 07:08.344
-as some of the others.
-THOMAS: Mm-hmm.

07:08.427 --> 07:10.721
Um, is there a reason or...

07:10.805 --> 07:14.225
The environment kind of begs
for you to go through the line

07:14.308 --> 07:15.685
-and then leave.
-NATHAN: Right.

07:15.768 --> 07:18.855
Uh, the physical space is asking
you not to be there. (CHUCKLES)

07:18.938 --> 07:21.149
Yeah. You know, you--
When you got your order,

07:21.232 --> 07:24.235
maybe spill it on the counter
and he would come to your aid,

07:24.318 --> 07:27.196
and that would break down some
of those social barriers

07:27.280 --> 07:28.865
that you're afraid to cross.

07:28.948 --> 07:31.325
-Just disrupt the situation?
-Yeah.

07:31.409 --> 07:32.910
And then maybe, you know,
it might lead

07:32.994 --> 07:35.371
to a more personal
conversation perhaps.

07:35.454 --> 07:37.790
Okay. Gotcha.

07:37.874 --> 07:41.127
NATHAN: When I relived the day
from Thomas's perspective,

07:41.210 --> 07:42.545
it proved my instincts

07:42.628 --> 07:43.921
-to be right.
-(ALL APPLAUD)

07:44.005 --> 07:46.174
Thomas, what about you?

07:46.257 --> 07:49.719
So, my primary
was at an acai bowl place.

07:49.802 --> 07:50.720
Acai bowl?

07:50.803 --> 07:52.722
Yeah. Acai bowl,
kind of like a smoothie.

07:52.805 --> 07:54.348
NATHAN: The circle felt
just as good

07:54.432 --> 07:58.019
from a student's perspective
as it was from the teacher's.

07:58.102 --> 08:01.480
And I felt really special
when Nathan pulled me aside

08:01.564 --> 08:03.858
to give me one-on-one guidance
after class.

08:03.941 --> 08:06.444
And that'll help break down
some of the social barriers

08:06.527 --> 08:08.029
that you're afraid to cross.

08:08.112 --> 08:10.364
-Thank you.
-All right? Good luck.
Good luck.

08:10.448 --> 08:11.782
-Thank you.
-Okay. Great.

08:11.866 --> 08:16.412
NATHAN: After reliving day two,
I basically found no issues.

08:16.495 --> 08:19.874
I felt Nathan gave every student
a lot of attention

08:19.957 --> 08:22.668
and made us feel comfortable
in the process.

08:23.836 --> 08:26.672
Maybe I had nothing to worry
about after all.

08:37.183 --> 08:38.267
♪ (MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

08:38.351 --> 08:40.311
NATHAN: It was nice
to be back in LA...

08:41.354 --> 08:42.939
back in my real home.

08:44.774 --> 08:47.902
Once in a while, I would try
to check in with Angela.

08:47.985 --> 08:49.153
(PHONE TRILLING)

08:58.496 --> 09:00.248
ALL: One, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.

09:00.331 --> 09:01.916
One, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.

09:01.999 --> 09:03.125
One, two, three.
One, two, three.

09:03.209 --> 09:04.585
One, two, three.
One, two, three.

09:04.669 --> 09:07.463
One, two. One, two. One, two.
One, two. One. One. One. One

09:07.546 --> 09:08.589
(CHEERS, CHUCKLES)

09:08.673 --> 09:10.341
-Wow! All right.
-ACTOR: Oh, my God.

09:10.424 --> 09:13.219
NATHAN: Now that the actors
had studied their primaries

09:13.302 --> 09:15.263
for two days...

09:15.346 --> 09:17.640
it was time to physically
embody them.

09:17.723 --> 09:22.770
♪ (WHIMSICAL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

09:24.063 --> 09:26.357
Um, you use tape
and string, is that...

09:27.692 --> 09:29.235
-I don't know.
-You don't know? Okay.

09:29.318 --> 09:31.153
-I don't know what's--
-Um... What's that tool here?

09:31.237 --> 09:33.322
But over here,
I got a couple things going.

09:33.406 --> 09:34.740
Um... This is a...

09:38.869 --> 09:39.912
tie iron.

09:39.996 --> 09:41.289
-Tie iron?
-Tie iron, yeah.

09:41.372 --> 09:43.082
-T-I-E?
-I believe so.

09:43.791 --> 09:45.418
Bananas under the cans.

09:46.252 --> 09:47.336
(CLICKS TONGUE)

09:47.420 --> 09:48.963
NATHAN: But I now knew
that to take on the mind

09:49.046 --> 09:52.800
of a stranger, it wasn't enough
to just talk to them.

09:52.883 --> 09:55.678
The level of immersion
had to be deeper.

09:55.761 --> 09:58.764
I am in the process of arranging
for all of you

09:58.848 --> 10:02.852
to work in the actual jobs
of your primary.

10:02.935 --> 10:05.896
Or at least as-- as close
as we can get.

10:07.273 --> 10:08.983
-Is that cool, pretty...
-ACTORS: Yeah.

10:09.066 --> 10:10.818
...or is that dumb?

10:10.901 --> 10:14.155
-I don't wanna work.
-(ALL LAUGH)

10:15.740 --> 10:17.533
NATHAN: I was noticing
the more extreme

10:17.616 --> 10:18.909
my method became,

10:18.993 --> 10:21.662
the more these actors seemed
to respect me.

10:21.746 --> 10:24.248
If I'm not gonna go all the way
and get out of my comfort zone,

10:24.332 --> 10:27.209
how am I gonna know
where I can go?

10:27.293 --> 10:30.504
So, yeah, thank you for just
the space, you know.

10:30.588 --> 10:33.883
NATHAN: But when I caught up
with Thomas, something felt off.

10:33.966 --> 10:35.885
Yeah, so-- so how did it go?
Yeah, what happened?

10:35.968 --> 10:37.553
-THOMAS: It was--
-Did you get personal? Did you?

10:37.636 --> 10:40.306
Yeah. The deeper conversation
was hard to accomplish.

10:40.389 --> 10:42.600
Did you spill your bowl
or anything? Or...

10:42.683 --> 10:44.602
-Did not spill the bowl.
-NATHAN: Okay, yeah.

10:44.685 --> 10:48.272
But I instead went with, uh...

10:48.356 --> 10:50.649
telling him that I lost
my lucky guitar pick

10:50.733 --> 10:51.901
that I got from my dad.

10:51.984 --> 10:53.069
-Okay.
-And then--

10:53.152 --> 10:54.695
-Is that true?
-No, that was a lie.

10:54.779 --> 10:55.863
-Oh, okay, okay, got it.
-Yeah.

10:55.946 --> 10:57.656
I mean, I don't really
like lying to people,

10:57.740 --> 10:59.867
-in general.
-Yeah, neither do I.

10:59.950 --> 11:01.494
-THOMAS: Yeah.
-Yeah.

11:01.577 --> 11:04.205
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(CHUCKLES)

11:04.288 --> 11:07.750
Yeah, I don't know. It's, uh,
it's weird, but...

11:07.833 --> 11:11.003
this is all so fascinating,
so what are you gonna do?

11:11.712 --> 11:12.546
Right.

11:12.630 --> 11:14.298
NATHAN:
Thomas's ambiguous emotions

11:14.382 --> 11:17.426
were hard for me to read,
but then I got the sense

11:17.510 --> 11:19.470
he had been uncomfortable
with this method

11:19.553 --> 11:21.263
since the very first day.

11:21.347 --> 11:22.807
So, yeah.
That's what makes me feel

11:22.890 --> 11:26.769
-kinda weird about it sometimes.
-About doing these-- this...

11:26.852 --> 11:29.772
...specific kind
of stalking thing. (CHUCKLES)

11:29.855 --> 11:31.107
The Fielder Method.

11:31.190 --> 11:34.151
NATHAN: Which was interesting
because I had not felt that

11:34.235 --> 11:35.444
when I was him.

11:40.241 --> 11:42.743
So rather than recreating
today's lesson,

11:42.827 --> 11:46.497
I decided to experience
that first day again

11:46.580 --> 11:48.916
to see
if I had missed something.

11:48.999 --> 11:50.418
-Hey, I'm Nathan.
-Thomas.

11:50.501 --> 11:52.837
-Thomas? Good to meet you.
-Yeah. Good to meet you.

11:52.920 --> 11:54.463
-Uh, yeah, have a seat.
-Sure, yeah.

11:54.547 --> 11:56.632
-And, uh, just hang out.
-Okay, great.

11:56.715 --> 11:58.551
NATHAN: This time, I was focused

11:58.634 --> 12:00.886
on really getting
into his mindset.

12:00.970 --> 12:03.973
So I just kept saying to myself
in my head,

12:04.056 --> 12:06.600
"Your name is Thomas
and you're an actor."

12:07.268 --> 12:08.602
"How do you feel?"

12:08.686 --> 12:11.605
I have a show that requires
a specific type

12:11.689 --> 12:14.650
-of performance.
-NATHAN: Almost immediately,

12:14.733 --> 12:18.446
I felt a rush of excitement come
over me when I remembered

12:18.529 --> 12:20.406
there were cameras filming me.

12:21.782 --> 12:23.367
HBO cameras.

12:24.368 --> 12:25.953
I love being on camera.

12:26.036 --> 12:30.249
But I wanted to play it cool,
like I didn't care that much.

12:30.332 --> 12:33.377
With this show, if your per--
if your performance

12:33.461 --> 12:34.587
isn't accurate...

12:35.880 --> 12:37.840
you could ruin someone's life.

12:37.923 --> 12:40.342
NATHAN: Wait, what is this show?

12:41.385 --> 12:43.929
Is this a show
about an acting class?

12:44.013 --> 12:48.309
Am I supposed to be acting?
Something doesn't make sense.

12:48.392 --> 12:51.061
If you're training actors
for a show,

12:51.145 --> 12:53.272
why would you be filming
the training?

12:54.356 --> 12:55.483
I wanted to ask,

12:55.566 --> 12:58.068
but I was worried
it would seem rude.

12:58.152 --> 13:03.157
I didn't wanna stand out.
I wanted to impress Nathan.

13:03.240 --> 13:05.367
